Sentiment Analysis

Pre-labeled sentiment from the data capture tool. Neutrals dominate (64%), reflecting factual information-sharing common in diabetes communities. Positive sentiment (26%) outweighs negative (7%).

Key Finding: The positive-to-negative ratio is 3.9:1, suggesting CGM technology is generally well-received by consumers. Instagram has the highest positive rate (~44%), likely due to advocacy and success-story sharing. Forums have the most balanced sentiment, reflecting genuine problem-solving discussions.

Brand & Competitive Landscape

Brand mentions detected via keyword matching across all consumer posts. Dexcom dominates the conversation by a wide margin, followed by Freestyle Libre and Tandem.

Brand Sentiment Scorecard

Key Finding: Dexcom leads in both volume (18,800+ mentions) and positive net sentiment. Freestyle Libre has the second-highest volume with strong positive sentiment among Type 2 and budget-conscious users. Medtronic shows notably higher negative sentiment, often linked to reliability and closed-loop system frustrations. The Dexcom G6 is the most-discussed specific model by far.

Consumer Discussion Topics

Topics identified via keyword-based classification of consumer posts. Medical/A1C and Insulin/Pumps lead, reflecting the clinical context of CGM use. Sensor issues and accuracy are top functional concerns.

Key Finding: Insurance & Cost is the topic with the highest negative sentiment rate — a major consumer pain point. App & Connectivity shows disproportionate negative sentiment, suggesting technology friction. Lifestyle & Daily Use has the highest positive rate, indicating consumers value the quality-of-life improvements from CGM.

Temporal Trends

Monthly volume and sentiment trends across the data capture period.

N-Gram Analysis

Most frequent two-word (bigram) and three-word (trigram) phrases across all consumer posts, after stopword removal. These reveal the core vocabulary and recurring phrases in the CGM consumer conversation.

Key Finding: "Blood sugar", "insulin pump", "dexcom g6", "finger stick", and "freestyle libre" are the most common bigrams. Trigrams reveal discussion of the healthcare system ("health care provider"), product ecosystems ("dexcom g6 sensor"), and management approaches ("continuous glucose monitor"). "Finger stick" prominence suggests accuracy comparison is a central consumer concern.

TF-IDF Discriminative Terms

Terms that best characterize each sentiment class using Term Frequency–Inverse Document Frequency weighting. Unlike raw frequency, TF-IDF highlights words that are distinctively important to each sentiment group.

Key Finding: Positive posts are characterized by terms like "love", "amazing", "game changer", "life changing", and specific brand names, suggesting brand loyalty and transformative experiences. Negative posts feature "insurance", "error", "frustrat", "pain", "fail", and "customer service" — pointing to the key friction areas. Neutral posts center on informational and clinical terms.

Sentiment-Distinctive Vocabulary

Log-odds ratio analysis identifying words most strongly associated with positive vs. negative sentiment. Words are filtered to those appearing in 50+ posts. The further from center, the more distinctively associated with that sentiment class.

Key Finding: "Love", "amazing", "great", "recommend", and "awesome" are the most distinctively positive words. On the negative side: "insurance", "denied", "frustrating", "error", and "customer" stand out. This confirms that the primary drivers of negative sentiment are systemic (insurance/cost) and technical (reliability), while positive sentiment is driven by life-quality improvement.

LDA Topic Model (Unsupervised)

Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) with 8 topics applied to the full corpus. Each topic is represented by its top 10 most probable words. This unsupervised approach discovers latent themes that co-occur in consumer text.

Source & Channel Analysis

Distribution of consumer posts across social media platforms and online communities.

Key Finding: Reddit forums dominate the dataset (89%), making this primarily a forum-based analysis. The diabetes-specific subreddits (r/diabetes_t1, r/diabetes, r/Type1Diabetes) provide rich, detailed consumer experiences. Instagram and Twitter provide shorter-form content with higher positive sentiment, likely biased toward advocacy and brand promotion.
